I served this Christmas morning for a crowd, and it was a hit with adults and children alike. The young kids were not thrilled with the cranberry-apple compote, however, so I was glad I had maple syrup available. The french toast was easy to prepare once I figured out how to cut the bread. Because my country bread was not very tall, I skipped cutting the loaf in half horizontally. This made fewer slices to turn during the cooking process, which was an advantage. The bread did not soak up all the custard mixture, so I had custard left over to use for a small batch of toast the next day. My husband and daughter loved it just as much the second time around. This recipe is so good it might become my new Christmas morning tradition.

